This is at the root of all escapism. The virgin heroines – among them Ola, Ludmilla, Shenda and Udalla – were of a piece: innocent but also sturdy in the face of villainous lechery from sadistic marquesses. Moral compasses were fully secured. Love was found with brusquely honest men who sometimes turned out to be aristocrats posing as commoners. Endings were happy – bathed in the pure love that came from heaven. "Lawful permanent residents, who live in the same county and speak English, can serve effectively as jurors." azuremedicalcentre.com.au There’s a two-Michelin-star restaurant next to Le Café de la Fontaine in La Turbie. It’s called Hostellerie Jérôme, and both places are run by Bruno Cirino, who used to work for me. He does haute cuisine de la marché – very simple, using produce from the market: roast duck with foie-gras, sea bass with a compôte of courgette flowers. Apart from Le Louis XV, there is only one place with three Michelin stars – La Vague d’Or in St-Tropez. It does haute cusine de la Mediterranée: amberjack fish and crabmeat marinaded in mandarin oranges, say, or turbot in a Camargue sea-salt crust with shellfish and rock samphire. It’s in a beautiful setting too, right by the water’s edge.
